body:
The qualified method call syntax (`<Type as Trait>::method()`) accepts both tyṕes and modules as the trait. This leads to some interesting errors.

```
fn main() {
    <f32 as f32>::ceil(1.0);
    <f32 as String>::ceil(1.0);
    <f32 as std>::ceil(1.0);
}
```

Results in

```
error[E0576]: cannot find method or associated constant `ceil` in `f32`
  |
2 |     <f32 as f32>::ceil(1.0);
  |                   ^^^^ not found in `f32`

error[E0576]: cannot find method or associated constant `ceil` in `String`
  |
3 |     <f32 as String>::ceil(1.0);
  |                      ^^^^ not found in `String`

error[E0576]: cannot find method or associated constant `ceil` in module `std`
  |
4 |     <f32 as std>::ceil(1.0);
  |                   ^^^^ not found in `std`
```

Reproduced on the playground: https://play.rust-lang.org/?version=stable&mode=debug&edition=2018&gist=f297c06425b789bcadfb75232f54bb8e
